.LONG TERM...
(Saturday through Thursday)
Issued at 350 AM PDT Fri Mar 21 2025

Zonal flow gives way to upper level ridging building late Saturday
into Sunday, which will be the start of the gradual warming trend.
High pressure continues to build and then hold through early next
week, leading to high temperatures being 5 to 15 degrees above
normal on Monday and Tuesday. The pattern begins to change late
Tuesday into Wednesday as upper level troughing develops over the
eastern Pacific. Cluster analysis and deterministic models favor a
more PacNW solution with rain chances for us favoring the North Bay
at this time from Wed through Friday. There`s still uncertainty on
timing and placement with this system so stay tuned to the forecast
for updates.

Looking beyond Day 7, the  CPC outlooks still highlight
leaning above normal chances for precipitation. Deterministic and
ensemble guidance favors a late March/early April shot at rain.
Given this is even more out in time there is still a lot time for
things to change, so be sure to check back as we get closer towards
the end of the month.

&&

.AVIATION...
(06Z TAFS)
Issued at 935 PM PDT Thu Mar 20 2025

VFR continues for the 06z TAFs except temporary patchy valley fog
/LIFR-IFR/ developing KSTS 12z-16z Friday morning.

Vicinity of SFO...VFR except 12z-16z Friday there may be patchy
broken to overcast cloud ceiling development nearby KSFO per boundary
layer humidity forecasts. West wind near 15 knots diminishing to
around 10 knots tonight then increasing to 15 knots Friday
afternoon and early evening.

SFO Bridge Approach...Similar to SFO.

Monterey Bay Terminals...VFR. West to northwest winds 10 knots early
to mid evening then light and variable winds tonight and Friday
morning. West to northwest winds 10 to 15 knots developing Friday
afternoon.

&&

.MARINE...
(Today through Wednesday)
Issued at 350 AM PDT Fri Mar 21 2025

A strong northwest breeze continues south of Point Pinos through
early Saturday with fresh winds to continue north of Point Pinos.
Strong northwest winds will become more widespread over the
coastal  waters beginning late Saturday with winds set to diminish
early next  week. Long period swell, at a period of 18 to 20
seconds, will  arrive by midweek with an increased risk of sneaker
waves.  Significant wave heights will build mid to late next week
as a low  pressure system moves into the PNW.

&&

